Requirements

data <- read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01b.csv")

Function for Step1 and Step2 :

function_12 = function(data, values){
  data2 <- data %>%
    select(Area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) %>%
    rename("area_name" = Area_name) %>%
    pivot_longer(cols = 3:12, names_to = "Char", values_to = "values")
  return(data2)
}

Function for Step3 :

function_3 = function(data2){
  data2$Measurement <- substr(data2$Char,1,7)
  data2$Year <- substr(data2$Char,8,9)
  data2$Year <- as.Date(data2$Year, format = "%y")
  data2$Year <- format(data2$Year, "%Y")
  data2$Year <- as.numeric(data2$Year)
  return(data2)
}

Function for Step5 :

function_5 = function(county){
  class(county) <- c("county", class(county))
  countyNew <- county %>%
  mutate(state = str_sub(area_name, start = -2, end = -1))
  return(countyNew)
}

Function for Step6 :

function_6 = function(state){
  Division1 <- c("CONNECTICUT", "MAINE", "MASSACHUSETTS", "NEW HAMPSHIRE", "RHODE ISLAND", "VERMONT")
  Division2 <- c("NEW JERSEY", "NEW YORK", "PENNSYLVANIA")
  Division3 <- c("ILLINOIS", "INDIANA", "MICHIGAN", "OHIO", "WISCONSIN")
  Division4 <- c("IOWA","KANSAS", "MINNESOTA", "MISSOURI", "NEBRASKA", "NORTH DAKOTA", "SOUTH DAKOTA")
  Division5 <- c("DELAWARE", "FLORIDA", "GEORGIA", "MARYLAND", "NORTH CAROLINA", "SOUTH CAROLINA", "VIRGINIA", "DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA", "District of Columbia", "WEST VIRGINIA")
  Division6 <- c("ALABAMA", "KENTUCKY", "MISSISSIPPI", "TENNESSEE")
  Division7 <- c("ARKANSAS", "LOUISIANA", "OKLAHOMA", "TEXAS")
  Division8 <- c("ARIZONA", "COLORADO", "IDAHO", "MONTANA", "NEVADA", "NEW MEXICO", "UTAH", "WYOMING")
  Division9 <- c("ALASKA", "CALIFORNIA", "HAWAII", "OREGON", "WASHINGTON")

  NE <- state[state$area_name %in% Division1,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "New England")
  
  MA <- state[state$area_name %in% Division2,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "Mid-Atlantic")
  
  ENC <- state[state$area_name %in% Division3,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "East North Central")

  WNC <- state[state$area_name %in% Division4,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "West North Central")

  SA <- state[state$area_name %in% Division5,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "South Atlantic")

  ESC <- state[state$area_name %in% Division6,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "East South Central")

  WSC <- state[state$area_name %in% Division7,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "West South Central")

  M <- state[state$area_name %in% Division8,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "Mounain")

  P <- state[state$area_name %in% Division9,] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "Pacific")

  E <- state[!state$area_name %in% c(Division1,Division2,Division3,Division4,Division5,Division6,Division7,Division8,Division9),] %>% 
  mutate(Division = "ERROR")
  state <- bind_rows(NE,MA,ENC,WNC,SA,ESC,WSC,M,P,E)
  return(state) 
}

Function for Step4, Step5 and Step6 :

function_456 = function(data2){
  state_indices <- grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", data2$area_name)
  county <-  subset(data2, row.names(data2) %in% state_indices)
  class(county) <- c("county", class(county))
  state <-  subset(data2, !(row.names(data2) %in% state_indices))
  class(state) <- c("state", class(state))
  county = function_5(county)
  state = function_6(state)
  return(list(county=county, state=state))
}

Wrapper Function :

my_wrapper <- function(url, default_var_name = "values"){
  a <- read_csv(url)
  b <- function_12(a, default_var_name )
  c <- function_3(b)
  d <- function_456(c)
  return(d)
}

Combining 2 outputs :

combined_outputs <- function(output1,output2){
  output3 <- bind_rows(output1$county,output2$county)
  output4 <- bind_rows(output1$state, output2$state)
  
  final_output <- list(county = output3, state = output4)
  
return(final_output)
}

Generic Funtion for Summarizing

This function plots the mean value of enrollment across the year for each Division. It also removes the observation at the Error setting of division.

plot.state <- function(df, var_name = "values"){
  new_df <- df %>%
    filter(Division != "ERROR") %>%
    group_by(Division, Year) %>%
    summarize(meanEnrollment = mean(get(var_name)))
  
  #print(new_df)
  ggplot(new_df, aes(x = Year, y = meanEnrollment , color = Division)) +geom_line()
}

This function is used to plot the enrollment data for counties across the year for each division. The arrangement of the states can be either top or bottom and slice_head() is used to get the top 5 rows.

plot.county <- function(df, var_name = "values", select_state = "AL", arrangement = "top", count= 5){
  new_df2 <- df %>%
    filter(state == select_state) %>%
    group_by(area_name) %>%
    summarize(meanEnrollment = mean(get(var_name)))
  if(arrangement == "top"){
    new_df2 <- new_df2 %>% arrange(desc(meanEnrollment)) %>% slice_head(n = count)
  } else if(arrangement == "bottom"){
    new_df2 <- new_df2 %>% arrange((meanEnrollment)) %>% slice_head(n = count)
  }
  final_df <- df %>% 
    filter(area_name %in% new_df2$area_name)
  
  ggplot(final_df, aes(x = Year, y = get(var_name), color = area_name)) +geom_line()
}
